1319 / 4                                                                        P$$, $$6324ac846493e942411a439704cf4cde08d337ae4beee9a486e7ce5f4d512279$$, $${"A": "2994e77e697f0f81d31f604560a97485643a62080c31191d3de356ccc43e4442", "C": "c63024c3ec35c6debb0401e50165144ffdab92593bc6a372fc97504eb1352b76", "D": "2ecd868b22b182cf83d910075eeb140289ed919086f21d5368cb288f8bd4f582"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Navy/RDTEN_BA4_Book.pdf$$, 1559, $$2026-05-10T04:04:19.242458+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0207147M$$, 2027, $$USMC Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA) is an uncrewed aircraft that enhances the survivability and lethality of the Marine Air Ground Task Force (MAGTF),
complementing the Service's current 4th/5th Generation Tactical Aircraft (TACAIR) capability. The uncrewed weapons systems under development will enhance Marine
Corps Aviation's lethality and ability to support the Stand-in Force (SiF) by delivering air-to-ground, reconnaissance, and Electronic Warfare (EW) capabilities. This PE
leverages OSW Rapid Defense Experimentation Reserve (RDER) investments to rapidly field an uncrewed aircraft capable of collaborative effects with expeditionary
manned aircraft (current 4th/5th Generation TACAIR) and amphibious forces as part of the Joint Force. Key attributes include enhanced survivability of tactical manned
aircraft, integrated autonomy and improved lethality against near-peer/peer threats. Program activities include employment of digital acquisitions via digital engineering,
agile software development, and open systems architecture. Funding provides critical infrastructure investments, operational concept exploration, technology studies,
multi-domain integration, operational assessments, architecture development, and multi-level prototyping towards a Minimum Viable Product (MVP), as well as program
management support. This effort also reduces risk towards enhanced technology development, integration and demonstration.

The FY 2026 spend plan for Collaborative Combat Aircraft includes $5,000 thousand of discretionary and $270,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total
of $275,000 thousand. FY 2026 total funding supports USMC Collaborative Combat Aircraft MUX TACAIR Increment I. The discretionary funds provide for rapid
prototyping, test and procurement with prime vendor. The mandatory funds provide for accelerated prototyping, test and procurement including four (4) MUX TACAIR
USMC CCA test articles for targeted squadron standup beginning in FY29.

JUSTIFICATION FOR BUDGET ACTIVITY: This program is funded under ADVANCED COMPONENT DEVELOPMENT AND PROTOTYPES because it includes all
efforts necessary to evaluate integrated technologies, representative models or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.
Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)$$, $$MAGTF Unmanned Aerial System Expeditionary Tactical Aircraft (MUX TACAIR) is a component of the USMC initiative to field a Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA)
capability that supports mass buildup of a Joint Force against a peer/near-peer adversary. Project efforts focus on operations from austere Expeditionary Advanced
Basing Operations (EABO) airfields in support of Marine Littoral Regiment (MLR) and/or Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU) operations serving as the Stand in Force
(SiF) for a Joint Force, providing lethal and flexible support to support from the land and sea. This project increases MAGTF lethality, capacity and interoperability in the
reconnaissance and electronic warfare mission areas, complementing existing and future TACAIR capabilities and enhancing combat reach into the INDOPACOM Area
of Responsibility (AoR), or wherever enhanced, stand-off lethality is needed by the Joint Force. MUX TACAIR will increase the survivability, lethality, interoperability, and
sustainability of the Marine Corps in support of the Joint Force.

