INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604286N$$, 2027, $$The Maritime Industrial Base's Deployable Advanced Manufacturing (AdvM) program conducts research, development, test and evaluation into various aspects of
AdvM technologies in order to enhance readiness and enhance capabilities for Navy warfighters. Specifically the program provides for the development of the AdvM,
to include Additive Manufacturing (AM, or 3D printing), process, material verification, and qualification to support deployment of AdvM/AM capability to Fleet Depot and
Level II Maintenance level facilities. It provides for the qualification, validation, testing and incorporation of private industry AM initiatives across the Naval Aviation
Enterprise to include NAVSUP and DLA. It funds Cooperative Research and Development Activities (CRADA) support with industry partners and next generation AM. It
funds the development, test, and approval of additional polymer material data curves, polymer material certification for aviation applications, and system documentation/
training updates of additional high strength polymers for use on deployed AM systems. This will support deployed systems in producing critical parts for aircraft, support
equipment and aircraft launch and recovery equipment, while enhancing Naval Aviation readiness and lethality allowing point of need part manufacturing to mitigate
supply chain gaps, dramatically decreasing Mean Logistics Delay Times (MLDT) and increasing aircraft availability. The program also funds investigation into the
development and use of AdvM equipment for Naval applications in land-based and afloat environments, including AdvM system performance requirements, shipboard
integration requirements and considerations, material selection, design optimization, equipment and component certification, and digital engineering integration. Efforts
also include consideration of AM across a wide variety of potential applications ensuring additively manufactured components can meet mission requirements and
that system/component technical requirements are updated to leverage AM. The program evaluates and identifies critical parts suitable for AdvM production in the
field; identifies AdvM systems appropriate to produce critical parts in tactical environments ashore; analyzes and identifies AdvM system implications across doctrine,
organization, training, materiel, leadership and education, personnel, facilities and policy (DOTMLPF-P); conduct end-user field training, field experimentation, and fleet
exercise technology insertion to validate AdvM system capability and systems integration issues. The program will also fund development of a digital manufacturing
environment that provides a scalable, secure, and Risk Management Framework (RMF)-compliant solution, transforming isolated AM capabilities into an integrated Navy
Fleet-wide manufacturing network, enabling real-time support, automated updates, and comprehensive visibility across all deployed AdvM assets.

The FY 2025 spend plan amount for Navy Advanced Manufacturing includes $5,192 thousand of discretionary and $186,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a
total of $191,192 thousand.
Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)$$, $$The AM program focuses on development and use of AM equipment for Naval applications in land-based and afloat applications, including system performance
requirements, shipboard/expeditionary/aviation integration requirements and considerations, material selection, design optimization, equipment and component
certification, and digital engineering integration. Efforts also include consideration of AM across a wide variety of potential applications ensuring AM manufactured
components can meet mission requirements and that system/component technical requirements are updated to leverage AM.

