INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604289M$$, 2027, $$Advanced Manufacturing Systems (AMS) includes a transformative capability for naval warfare and expeditionary operations, harnessing the power of both additive (3D
printing) and subtractive manufacturing. This technology is a strategic game-changer, equipping the Marine Corps with a decisive advantage in readiness, sustainment,
and lethality. By radically compressing the design-to-production cycle, AMS empowers Marines at the forward edge of the battlefield with the autonomy to solve
problems on demand.

 As this capability evolves, it holds the key to resolving chronic supply chain vulnerabilities like obsolescence, diminishing manufacturing sources (DMSMS), and long
 lead times?challenges that will become even more acute in future Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations (EABO) and Distributed Operations (DO). The ability to
 manufacture critical components and even entire platforms at the point of need will forge a new era of logistical resilience, creating a scalable and highly responsive
 supply chain that directly supports the warfighter.$$, $$This project supports costs associated with the research, development, testing and evaluation of Marine Corps Systems Command acquisition process modifications,
prototyping, and future logistics innovations to support the USMC Advanced Manufacturing Systems (AMS) Initiative. This project invests in the 3D printing and
machining capability with both metals and polymers.

 This process establishes a comprehensive digital data repository that enables seamless sharing of equipment, technical data, and part designs. It enforces a rigorous
 part approval workflow, integrates engineering analysis and testing, and drives the production of prototype parts. Concurrently, it develops targeted training programs to
 ensure the Marine Corps fully leverages advanced manufacturing programs of record.

 This initiative actively forges strategic partnerships with Department of Navy (DoN) Systems Commands and field activities to define and implement DoN-wide
 standards, processes, and acquisition protocols. These efforts directly support the integration of additive manufacturing into DoN acquisition, readiness, and
 sustainment, ensuring a standardized, efficient, and future-ready manufacturing framework.

