INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604320M$$, 2027, $$The Marine Corps Rapid Capabilities Office (MCRCO) focuses on the accelerating technological changes the battlefield has been met with and the constant evolution
of threats. Established under the direct authority of the Commandant of the Marine Corps, the MCRCO operates with a singular, urgent purpose: to cut through
bureaucratic inertia and rapidly deliver game-changing capabilities directly into the hands of the Fleet Marine Forces. Its mission is to identify, develop, and transition
emergent and disruptive technologies that provide a decisive edge, significantly enhancing the survivability, lethality, and overall effectiveness of every Marine on the
battlefield.

 Unlike traditional, multi-year acquisition programs, the MCRCO is built for speed, focusing on mature, cutting-edge technologies that can be fielded in months, not
 years. The office specifically targets solutions that have reached a Technology Readiness Level (TRL) of 7 or higher. This is a critical distinction. A TRL 7 designation
 signifies that a system is well beyond the conceptual or laboratory stage; it is a functioning prototype that has been successfully demonstrated in a realistic, operational
 environment. By concentrating on this level of maturity, the MCRCO minimizes developmental risk and drastically shortens the timeline from initial concept to combat-
 ready capability. Their process is a relentless cycle of rapid prototype development, rigorous testing, and seamless integration, all designed to ensure that when a new
 piece of gear arrives, it works as promised and integrates flawlessly with existing systems.

 To achieve this velocity, the MCRCO employs an agile and pragmatic sourcing strategy. It is not limited to a single development pipeline; rather, it leverages the best
 solutions available, regardless of their origin. This includes harnessing proven government-developed systems, adapting Commercial Off-the-Shelf (COTS) products
 from the private sector, and advancing promising developmental items that are on the cusp of a breakthrough. This flexible approach allows the MCRCO to act as a
 critical bridge, pulling technology from a wide array of innovators and pushing it to the warfighter who needs it most.

 Ultimately, the MCRCO plays an indispensable role in maintaining the Marine Corps' strategic readiness and technological superiority. It functions as the leading edge
 of modernization, ensuring that the Fleet Marine Forces are not just prepared for the conflicts of today, but are armed with the disruptive tools necessary to dominate the
 battlefields of tomorrow. By providing this accelerated pathway for innovation, the MCRCO guarantees that the Marine Corps can adapt faster than its adversaries and
 continue its legacy as the nation's premier expeditionary force in readiness.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Rapid Prototype Development; Marine Corps Rapid Capabilities Office (MCRCO) includes $72,519 thousands of discretionary and
 $18,500 thousands of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $91,019 thousands.
Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)$$, $$Wing-in-Ground-effect (WIG) platforms are an emerging alternative maritime transportation capability that will disrupt the adversaries kill chain and result in a cost
imposition on enemy targeting. WIG platforms have potential to fill capability gaps in the Marine Corps' family of Littoral-Maritime Transportation & Mobility Systems.
WIGs are water borne, inexpensive, maneuverable, platforms offering an alternative mode of high-speed surface transportation in a contested maritime, anti-access/area
denial (A2AD) environment. Operating in ground effect provides maximum operational efficiency and allows the vessels to be certified as a maritime platform vice an
aircraft, reducing certification and training requirements.

