B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                             FY 2027    FY 2027       FY 2027
                                                                                                                        FY 2025   FY 2026    Base       OOC           Total
- Develop and Integrate Advanced Small UAS Capabilities. Continue to sustain fielded First-Person View (FPV)
drone systems to inform operational feedback while focusing on developing and prototyping critical upgrades.
Funding will support the rapid development of advanced Ground Control Stations (GCS), the maturation of
software for enhanced autonomous navigation and C2 integration, and the creation of innovative training
methodologies for testing and evaluation.
- Accelerate Prototyping and Demonstration of One-Way Attack (OWA) Systems. Expedite the development and
operational demonstration of the Low-Cost Unmanned Aerial System (LUCAS) family of systems. This initiative
transitions a promising S&T concept into a rapid prototyping and experimentation effort to mature the system for
potential future fielding. The funding increase from FY26 to FY27 is essential to conduct the following efforts:
- Demonstrate scalable manufacturing and reduce prototype costs by refining manufacturing processes,
identifying cost-reduction opportunities, and demonstrating the potential for scalable production. Initial
prototyping aims to validate that per-unit costs can be driven down to the $70K range in larger quantities, a key
performance parameter for the system's viability.
- Mature system integration via rapid prototyping by supporting the iterative research, development, and
testing required to integrate LUCAS prototypes into a cohesive digital kill web. This includes developing and
experimenting with software interfaces to automate sensor data transfer, testing integration with C2 systems,
and demonstrating a common operating picture for small units. This prototyping effort is critical to mitigating risk
and maturing the technology for the sensor-to-shooter workflow.
- Develop and test a complete experimental system package. This includes iterating on the designs for GCSs,
Ground Support Equipment, antennas, launchers, and inert training warheads to create a viable system for
operational assessment.
- Develop and refine training and employment concepts through rigorous operational experimentation. This
involves creating draft operator/maintenance manuals, testing virtual training simulators, and conducting New
Equipment Training (NET) with select fleet units to gather feedback and inform the final system configuration and
future doctrine.
FY 2027 OOC Plans:
N/A
