INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604536N$$, 2027, $$The Department encourages additional vendor participation in the design, development, and production of alternative weapons systems to meet current and future
warfighting requirements. With current major weapons systems production at capacity, the nation is looking for alternative systems to fill these gaps. The Department is
implementing diverse procurement strategies to enable rapid acquisition. These will include the use of Other Transaction Authorities, 'Marketplace' acquisition platforms,
and alternative concepts to increase supply and suppliers in addition to traditional FAR-based procurement strategies.

The United States Navy is executing a significant strategic pivot towards ensuring and advancing its dominance in the undersea domain by consolidating all of its
Unmanned Undersea Vehicle (UUV) efforts under a single, unified portfolio. Known as the Advanced Undersea Prototyping (AUP) Program Element, this initiative
centralizes all Research, Development, Testing, and Evaluation (RDT&E) for the UUV Family of Systems. This portfolio approach is a direct manifestation of the Chief
of Naval Operations' broader "hedge strategy," which is focused on creating a more agile and adaptable force by integrating, experimenting with, and maturing new
technologies to counter emerging threats.

At its core, the AUP portfolio is designed to incubate a diverse range of capabilities, allowing the Navy to pursue multiple technology pathways simultaneously. By
developing platforms in various sizes and configurations, the Navy is systematically examining and closing capability gaps, such as counter-UxS warfare, while building
the capacity needed for future requirements. This strategy allows the Navy to deliver a variety of critical capabilities to the warfighter, reinforcing goals of undersea
dominance, seabed control, and non-traditional sea denial through a hedge fleet of manned and unmanned systems. As a result of this portfolio there will a more
survivable, lethal force in theater, assured control of the strategic seabed, protecting friendly C5ISR links while holding adversary infrastructure at risk, and a scalable,
on-demand capability to shape the battlespace, gain or deny access to key maritime areas, and impose prohibitive costs on an adversary.

This strategic focus on integration and experimentation is evident in the diverse projects managed within the portfolio. For instance, Project 3394, the "Adv Undersea
Prototyping-Vehicles, Propulsion & Navigation," includes the Extra Large Unmanned Undersea Vehicle (XLUUV) known as Orca. The Orca features a modular payload
bay, showcasing the focus on integrating new systems. In parallel, the Combat Autonomous Maritime Platform (CAMP) project leverages commercial prototypes for
rapid capability demonstrations to meet specific INDOPACOM requirements, highlighting the emphasis on experimentation, this is the next-gen XLUUV system. Other
 innovative approaches include the Liberator program, a stationary system placed on the seabed to launch various payloads. The Hunter program is a modular payload
 designed to support multiple XL platforms based. The Dragonfish 2094 project is a UUV designed to attack surface targets and infrastructure. To modernize existing
 capabilities, Project 4023 includes the Lionfish small UUV and its deep-water variant, the Viperfish medium UUV, to enhance mine countermeasures and other undersea
 missions. This domain-centered portfolio of unmanned systems will support the development and integration of mission specific sensors and payloads to support current
 and future mission requirements.

Ultimately, all of these individual programs and technologies are unified under the Undersea Fleet Operations and Testing program. This crucial element of the portfolio
manages the government-led development, rigorous operational testing, and final Fleet integration for the entire UUV Family of Systems. This ensures that the advanced
technologies being matured within the AUP portfolio are not merely experimental concepts but are effectively transitioned into fully operational systems that provide a
tangible advantage to the warfighter.

The FY 2026 spend plan for Orca Extra Large Unmanned Undersea Vehicle (XLUUV) includes $143,943 Thousand of discretionary funding and $199,408 thousand of
mandatory for a total of $343,351 thousand.$$, $$The Combat Autonomous Maritime Platform (CAMP) project will conduct competitive Extra Large Unmanned Undersea Vehicle capability demonstrations leveraging
commercial sources and non-developmental prototypes in accordance with FY25 NDAA section 1032. The project will use the Defense Innovation Unit's (DIU)
Commercial Solution Opening (CSO) process, prototyping, and spiral development. Systems will be assessed on vehicle range, payload capacities, and technical
maturity to meet Indo-Pacific Command requirements.

