D. Acquisition Strategy
Orca XLUUV is a multi-phased accelerated acquisition effort using USC Sec. 2358 authorities to rapidly deliver capability to the Fleet. Phase 1 was a competitively
sourced design effort. Two design contracts were awarded to Boeing and Lockheed Martin in FY 2017. Phase 2 commenced with a down select in FY 2019 to Boeing
for fabrication and testing of the vehicle and support elements. Five Orca XLUUV operationally relevant prototype systems (vehicles, mobile C2 equipment, and support
equipment) are being fabricated for demonstration and for use by the Fleet. A test and training asset (XLE0) was added to the contract in March 2022 and delivered to
the Navy in FY24 to support early learning, prototyping, training, and in-water risk reduction testing..

In addition, the CAMP is a prototype project using USC 4022 authorities to assess commercial XLUUV capabilities. The Navy is conducting prototyping for extended
range, large payload commercially available UUV platforms through a DIU CSO using a three phase strategy of written proposal evaluations, in-water demonstration
assessments and cost, schedule, performance negotiations.

The acquisition strategy for the Liberator program centers on a full and open competition for multiple prototyping Other Transaction Agreements (OTAs) to foster
innovation and competition among industry partners. This prototyping phase will cover the design, fabrication, and testing of the Liberator system. The results will directly
inform the government's decision to award follow-on production OTAs to successful partners. The goal is to award prototyping OTAs by Q3FY26 and receive prototype
systems by FY27.

