surveillance, or hostile threats posed from the inadvertent or unlawful misuse of unmanned aircraft systems (UAS). The C-UAS program provides an integrated Family of
Systems (FoS) employing advanced target discrimination and defeat capabilities to meet fleet requirements. More details available at a higher classification level.

FY 2027 funding is requested to continue management and implementation of system assessment. Provide program management and systems engineering support
for the technology development and acquisition strategy for fielding material solution. Funding provides for refinement of material solutions, threat assessments,
identification and development of advanced target discrimination, defeat capabilities, and prototype development for integration into the C-UAS FoS.

Continues refinement of open architecture solution and interoperability standards for a C-UAS FoS. In partnership with the Joint C-UAS Office (JCO), will identify
or develop additional detect and deter capabilities to integrate into the C-UAS FoS. As the JCO designated CORIAN Acquisition Lead, continued development,
implementation and integration of additional sensor modalities to improve system detect/ID/track/defeat capabilities. Continues efforts to improve interoperability
between ashore and afloat C-UAS systems.$$, $$The Counter small Unmanned Aerial Systems (C-sUAS) Family of Systems (FoS) program was funded to provide initial material solutions to SECNAV-prioritized
locations CONUS and OCONUS with baseline electronic warfare (EW) capabilities to detect, track, identify, and defeat sUAS over a large coverage area. Following
initial material deployment, the program continues to expand the capabilities of select, high priority systems and adapt new solutions to defeat evolving threats. The
initial material solution included CORIAN, Ninja, DroneDefender, and DroneBuster. Expanded solutions include EO/IR, radar, C2, new EW detect/defeat capabilities,
alternative sensors, and additional kinetic and non-kinetic mitigations needed to prepare, maintain, and upkeep force protection, self-defense and operational capabilities
against the ever-evolving sUAS threat. Funding is provided to protect high-value and/or critical Navy assets and support public safety against threats by inadvertent or
unlawful misuse of sUAS.

FY27 increase will provide system assessments, intra-service technology capitalization, and refinement of open architecture solutions and interoperability standards of
fixed facility Navy Sites with joint C-UxS systems and with C-UxsS syetms on Navy Ships. Funding also provides for government engineering support for the technology
development and acquisition strategy for fielding material solutions that will help C-Uxs systems to evolve to rapidly evolving UAS capabilities.

