D. Acquisition Strategy
OASuW Inc 2 provides a generational advancement in OASuW capability. It will leverage significant Science & Technology progress on critical technologies, making
targeted investments to meet the demanding environmental and tactical requirements of carrier-launched aviation.

 The Navy plans to follow a competitive, phased approach with initial activities focusing on system concepts, model-based systems engineering, preliminary design and
 technology development efforts. The Navy will also use the lessons learned from emerging vendors and new acquisition approaches, such as those employed by the
 Multi-mission Affordable Capacity Effector (MACE) program, to maximize value to the Warfighter while reducing risk to the taxpayer.

 The Navy anticipates extensive use of Digital Engineering (DE) and Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) practices for requirements, design, trade studies,
 and analyses; as well as the use of DE/MBSE to accomplish technical planning for qualification, component/subsystem testing, manufacturing, and sustainment of the
 system under representative operational
 conditions in future phases of the program. The Navy also plans to use increased cadence of subsystem and system test to accelerate discovery and improve
 confidence in both the acquisition strategy and in the ultimate material solution.




