A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The V-22 Osprey provides a dual-piloted, multi-engine, Vertical/Short Takeoff and Landing, medium lift aircraft for worldwide combat, combat support, combat service
support, and Special Operations missions. V-22 Product Improvements addresses requirements necessary to meet the aircraft capabilities specified in the approved
Capability Development Document. Efforts included in this Project provide near and long-term improvements to the fleet, addressing deficiencies, systems safety,
obsolescence, readiness, reliability, supportability, and relevance in any designated battlespace. Efforts include hardware and software development associated with
increased performance capability, avionics upgrades and improvements, increased system processing capability, and the integration with other organic and non-organic
systems.

FY 2027 continues Airframe Hardware Development in support of V-22 Block upgrades, electrical system capacity efforts, digital interoperability, time on wing/reliability
improvements efforts, Aircraft Mission Maneuvering Envelope Expansion and Safety Improvement efforts. Continues engineering, logistics, flight test, flight test support
and addresses correction of deficiencies and obsolescence. Continues software development/mission computer obsolescence initiatives. Continues efforts to resolve
Fuel Cell obsolescence issues.

FY 2027 continues Propulsion/Mission Care Hardware Development to fund the flight/engine hours that are necessary for the design, development, validation and
verification of the V-22 propulsion and power systems at the Patuxent River squadron. Rolls-Royce will continue to provide engine support and development of V-22
flight testing.

FY 2027 continues Flight Control System (FCS) re-design. Flight control re-design improves safety and handling of platform by reducing workload in critical places like
degraded visual environment/reduced visual landing, aerial refueling, shipboard operations, and inclement weather situations through hardware and software changes.

FY 2027 continues Open Systems Architecture/Cyber Security research, requirements analysis and development of obsolescence mitigation solutions for aging V-22
avionics systems to overcome obsolete hardware availability. Replacement systems will be designed to provide compatibility with all legacy interfaces and functions
while resolving deficiencies, meeting expanding needs, and leveraging emerging hardware and software technologies to mitigate future obsolescence.

FY 2027 funding for the V-22 Cockpit Technology Refresh (VeCToR) will enhance the V-22 platform by improving critical safety and flight control systems, lowering long-
term sustainment costs, and ensuring operational efficiency and mission readiness through 2055. Begins flight controls augmented capability which improves safety
and handling of platform by reducing workload in critical places like degraded visual environment/reduced visual landing, aerial refueling, shipboard operations, and



