INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0605513N$$, 2027, $$The Department encourages additional vendor participation in the design, development, and production of alternative weapons systems to meet current and future
warfighting requirements. With current major weapons systems production at capacity, the nation is looking for alternative systems to fill these gaps. The Department is
implementing diverse procurement strategies to enable rapid acquisition. These will include the use of Other Transaction Authorities, 'Marketplace' acquisition platforms,
and alternative concepts to increase supply and suppliers in addition to traditional FAR-based procurement strategies.

This Research, Development, Test, and Evaluation (RDT&E) Program Element (PE) executes the CNO's Hedge Strategy by funding the development, maturation,
and integration of the Unmanned Surface Vehicle (USV) Family of Systems (FoS). The PE develops and tests the Tailored Offsets required to augment the main battle
force, as mandated by the CNO's Fighting Instructions. The objective is to create and validate capabilities across a range of critical mission areas, including kinetic and
non-kinetic effects, containerized multi-mission payloads, contested logistics, and Counter-Unmanned Aircraft Systems (CUAS). This PE funds the engineering and
experimentation for the entire USV FoS, which includes systems such as the Medium Unmanned Surface Vehicle (MUSV), Small USV Family of Systems (sUSV FoS),
Expeditionary One Way Attack (ExOWA), and the Autonomous Low Profile Vessel (ALPV), to forge a decisive warfighting advantage. This domain-centered portfolio
of unmanned systems will support the integration of mission specific sensors and payloads to support current and future mission requirements, such as Intelligence
Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR), Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW), and Strike Warfare (STW) missions.

The program functions as the foundry for unmanned surface warfare, transforming concepts and technology into validated, production-ready capabilities. It addresses
the CNO's imperative to integrate Robotic and Autonomous Systems (RAS) into the standard force delivery model by establishing common interfaces, standards, and
software for the portfolio. Through a warfighter-centric approach focused on rapid innovation and iterative testing, this PE prioritizes continuous experimentation to
convert innovation into proven, effective capabilities ready for transition to procurement.

The development activities within this PE enable a cohesive, mission-driven unmanned force design capable of executing Distributed Maritime Operations (DMO). The
validated systems and technologies that result from this RDT&E effort provide the foundational designs for an agile and mobile force, intended to confound adversary
detection and targeting and enable the fleet to seize and maintain the initiative.
of $319,042 thousand.$$, $$Expeditionary Maritime Sensing Systems and AUSVs for Manned-Unmanned Teaming efforts consist of Perception, Automated Target Recognition (ATR), Track
Management, Mission and Collaborative Autonomy (MCA), and Autonomous Command & Control (C2):

Perception, Automated Target Recognition (ATR), and Track Management:

Perception, Automatic Target Recognition (ATR), and track management are foundational autonomy capabilities supporting multiple mission sets for Robotics
Autonomous Systems (RAS), including One-Way Attack (OWA), Maritime Domain Awareness (MDA), Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR), and
Counter-UxS operations across theaters.

Perception capabilities enable unmanned platforms to ingest and process data from onboard sensors, such as EO/IR, radar, and other sensors, to detect objects and
characterize the surrounding environment. Building on this perception layer, ATR algorithms classify and identify detected objects, while track management capabilities
maintain persistent awareness of contacts over time, enabling platforms to track, prioritize, and support engagement decisions.

Together, these capabilities reduce the need to transmit raw sensor data back to operators, enabling scalable mission execution across large numbers of distributed
unmanned platforms. By allowing UxS to autonomously detect, classify, track, prioritize, and in some cases engage targets, these technologies significantly reduce
operator burden while enabling massed effects in Distributed Maritime Operations (DMO).

Structured, large-scale data collection provides the operationally relevant datasets required to develop, train, test, and sustain perception and ATR models across
diverse environments, sensors, and mission scenarios. Test events validate both model performance and the operational utility of collected data to inform future
collection priorities. Coupled with CI/CD pipelines and fleet-relevant data infrastructure, this approach enables rapid iteration, validation, and deployment of perception,
ATR, and track management capabilities across heterogeneous UxS platforms.

Mission and Collaborative Autonomy (MCA):

The Mission and Collaborative Autonomy (MCA) capability delivers mission-level autonomy that enables heterogenous UxS to use ATR to decide, coordinate, and
execute tactically optimized actions under commander's intent. Platform autonomy includes a native multi-input sense making stack that produces local awareness; MCA
ingests that local awareness, plus additional awareness from other UxS, non-native sensors, and payloads to produce an amplified, fused situational understanding.
MCA can then assign or reassign group tasks, augment or override local platforms Actions based on mission parameters, and deconflict group behavior to achieve
coordinated effects. MCA functions both onboard platforms (local mission execution) and at remove control stations (supervisory mission planning and distributed

                                                                                EHICLE ENABLING CAPABILITIES
coordination), and relies on resilient communications, secure data brokering, and integrated ATR/perception services to enable scalable, survivable manned-unmanned
teaming in contested environment.

Autonomous Command & Control (C2):

C2 ecosystem provides a resilient, multi-echelon command-and-control (C2) and orchestration framework for large numbers of unmanned systems (UxS) across
Maritime Operations Centers (MOCs), Joint Operations Centers (JOCs), Unmanned Operations Centers (UOCs), and host platforms. This architecture integrates
data sources with UxS C2 networks, enabling operations and commanders at multiple echelons to deploy high-level distributed unmanned mission in near-real time
without the need to plan, task, monitor, and dynamically retask individual assets. Through a unified C2 framework and data-broker layer, the system supports one-to-
many supervisory control of heterogenous UxS, synchronized with joint fires networks and operational C2 systems. Resilient networking, redundant data pathways,
and a common operational interface fuse sensor data, autonomy status, and mission tasking into a coherent operational picture. This enterprise C2 capability enables
coordinated employment of masses unmanned systems across domains, shortening decision cycles, increasing lethality and mission effectiveness, and reducing
operator workload in contested environments.

