FY 2025 Accomplishments: Perception, Automated Target Recognition (ATR), and Track Management:

In FY25, the program developed a scalable integration framework enabling third-party Automatic Target
Recognition (ATR) models to interface with the enterprise autonomy architecture. This framework allowed
rapid integration and evaluation of vendor-developed ATR capabilities, accelerating capability insertion from
the commercial and defense industrial base. The framework was demonstrated in support of the Replicator
Initiative during several on-water test events, where four vendors integrated ATR models onto USV platforms
for testing and validation. The program also developed mission-specific ATR capabilities supporting the One-
Way Attack (OWA) mission, which were evaluated during multiple on-water test events. In parallel, the team
initiated development and analysis of datasets required to train algorithms capable of detecting and interpreting
maritime day shapes and navigation lights, supporting improved perception in complex maritime environments.
Additionally, the program began developing a standardized evaluation framework and associated performance
metrics to assess and characterize perception and ATR models against defined mission requirements. This
framework will enable consistent evaluation of competing solutions and inform technology downselect decisions.
Delivery of this capability is planned for FY26.

Autonomous Command-and-Control:

                                                                               EHICLE ENABLING CAPABILITIES

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                 FY 2025   FY 2026

FY25 accomplishments included the delivery of a minimum viable product (MVP) in support of the INDOPACOM
mission, demonstrating the ability for a single operator to manage and control multiple RAS platforms. This one-
operator-to-many capability represented a significant step toward scalable unmanned operations. The effort also
included training fleet personnel to ensure operational readiness prior to fleet exercises and demonstrations.
Additionally, C2 capabilities were deployed on CANES-enabled surface combatants through the Overmatch
Application Arsenal, enabling integration of unmanned system control within existing naval system environments.
FY25 efforts also supported multiple fleet exercises and operational demonstrations with international partners,
during which tactical control of unmanned systems was successfully transferred between partner nations,
demonstrating interoperability.

Furthermore, C2 development efforts supported the integration and deployment of Seahawk in support of
USVRON1 activities taking place in FY26.
FY 2026 Plans: Perception, Automated Target Recognition (ATR), and Track Management:

In FY26, the program will expand Perception and Automatic Target Recognition (ATR) capabilities to support
operational mission requirements across multiple theaters. This effort will scale operational data collection
across Fifth, Sixth, Fourth, and Seventh Fleet areas of responsibility, leveraging a mix of RAS platforms,
commercial vessels, and manned assets to capture realistic sensor data across diverse maritime environments.
These datasets will support the development, training, and evaluation of operational ATR models aligned with
key mission requirements including One-Way Attack (OWA), Maritime Domain Awareness (MDA), Intelligence,
Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR), and counter-UAS operations.

FY26 activities will leverage enterprise DevSecOps pipelines to enable large-scale data labeling, curation, and
model development while supporting continuous testing and improvement of perception and ATR algorithms.
The program will competitively award Other Transaction Authorities (OTAs) to integrate and evaluate operational
ATR models across multiple USV platforms, with deployments alongside operational units supporting fleet
missions to validate mission performance in realistic conditions.

In parallel, ATR capabilities will be integrated with the broader perception stack, TrackFusion capabilities,
ICS and the Navy's C2 ecosystem, enabling persistent target detection, tracking, and classification across
distributed RAS platforms. Integration with Vehicle Mission and Collaborative Autonomy (MCA) will enable
coordinated sensing, tracking, and engagement of targets at scale, supporting Distributed Maritime Operations

                                                                               EHICLE ENABLING CAPABILITIES

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026
and increasing mission effectiveness across the fleet. The first operational ATR models are planned for testing
and validation on USV-1 by the end of Q1 FY27, followed by integration across additional USV platforms by the
end of FY26.

Autonomous Command-and-Control

In FY26, efforts will continue the maturation and operational deployment of the Navy's Command and Control
(C2) ecosystem, initially awarded under a production Other Transaction Authority (OTA) in FY26. Activities
will focus on delivering critical C2 capabilities in support of Fourth Fleet's Iron Sentinel operations, while
expanding those capabilities to support U.S. Fifth Fleet and U.S. Sixth Fleet counter-UAS missions. FY26 efforts
will also lay the groundwork for the C2 capabilities required to operationalize Medium USVs. Development
activities will focus on ensuring the C2 architecture can support scalable mission control across distributed
operational environments. Additional C2 capabilities will be developed in FY26 to enable mass deployment
of RAS across multiple theaters and mission sets. This includes the initial deployment of the C2 system in
operational environments, with infrastructure supporting both afloat platforms and shore-based control nodes,
enabling persistent command, monitoring, and tasking of distributed unmanned assets. FY27 will also build upon
sensor integration activities initiated in FY26, including integration with Minotaur and Maven Smart Systems,
as well as alignment with other high-priority Department of War initiatives. This includes integration with the
Defense Innovation Unit (DIU) C2 Orchestrator capability, which is planned to transition to PAE RAS in FY27 to
further support enterprise-level unmanned system command and control. These efforts will continue to advance
a scalable, interoperable C2 architecture capable of supporting distributed unmanned operations across multiple
operational theaters.
