Description: The Mission and Collaborative Autonomy (MCA) capability delivers mission-level autonomy that
enables heterogenous UxS to use ATR to decide, coordinate, and execute tactically optimized actions under
commander's intent. Platform autonomy includes a native multi-input sense making stack that produces local
awareness; MCA ingests that local awareness, plus additional awareness from other UxS, non-native sensors,
and payloads to produce an amplified, fused situational understanding. MCA can then assign or reassign
group tasks, augment or override local platforms Actions based on mission parameters, and deconflict group
behavior to achieve coordinated effects. MCA functions both onboard platforms (local mission execution) and
at remove control stations (supervisory mission planning and distributed coordination), and relies on resilient
communications, secure data brokering, and integrated ATR/perception services to enable scalable, survivable
manned-unmanned teaming in contested environment.

FY 2026 Plans:
Although Project 3067 was zeroed in PB26, the accomplishments below reflect work executed under PB25
funding, with some activities continuing into early FY26.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
In FY27, efforts will focus on maturing mission-level and collaborative autonomy capabilities to enable
heterogeneous groups of unmanned systems to operate cohesively in support of priority operational missions.
These capabilities will support One-Way Attack (OWA), Maritime Domain Awareness (MDA), and contested
logistics while enabling manned-unmanned teaming to increase operational effectiveness and distributed
maritime effects.

Key focus areas include the development of collaborative autonomy behaviors that allow multiple unmanned
platforms, including surface and aerial vehicles, to share relevant mission data, coordinate actions, and execute
missions more effectively in a distributed operational environment. These capabilities will enable platforms to
operate as coordinated teams rather than independent assets.


